If you look in the definition of `config_option::set()` (file "options.cc"), you'll see that it is defined as
```
void config_option::set(const PKArgs& args) { 
    setter(args[0].to_oobj()); 
}
```
Here `setter` is the option-setter function specified when the option was declared. For example, `set_ups()` is one such setter function; `set_min_duration()` is another. 
Inside `config_option::set()`, the name of the option is already known: it is `config_option::name` (unfortunately, it is not the same as `args[0]`). Hence, there should be no need to pass it along explicitly: the signature of the setter function can be updated so that it takes a `const Arg&` instead of an `oobj`.

